Text: Also, coming to cancelling. You can't logically cancel someone. Their opinions, their behaviour, their stubborn refusal to change for eg JKR.... You can 'cancel' those with opinions driven by facts and lived experience. Mere outrage + Twitter cancelation doesn't course correct.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Calling out is drawing attention to something that is problematic. Which the person tweeting may not be entirely aware of. If they seem willing to learn and understand, show them what's wrong. Help them help themselves to understand. Not talking about paid troll accounts, obvs.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Your observation shouldn't be colored by your 'pity' for them. Hear to listen. Listen to understand. Pay attention to observe. Observe to ask questions. Ask questions to challenge status quo. Challenge it to change your opinions, mindset, & behaviour. Individual/community level.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Don't limit your learning to the drivers or delivery executives or to your domestic help. Go beyond. Observe closely, ask questions, read up. Call out entitled tweets on people who belong to different class/professions/jobs/castes. Don't shame, it hampers learning and change.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Lived experiences being blogged on Instagram is another place I learn so much from. Listen to those at the grassroots. If the cab or auto driver is who you listen to on news, civic issues, politics, perspectives on a popular film, etc, then pay attention. nothing 'wrong' in it.

Text: What are other sources to gain information and knowledge from? Read to understand first. Opinions can be formed afterwards. I like Facebook better for this. Thoughts are articulated and discussions in comments easier to follow.

Text: Shape your own politics, fact-check for yourself. If something is being said by a person whose politics or political affiliations are something you admire, and you feel conflicted by something. Don't accept it. Ask questions. Take what you feel is right. Accept when you are wrong

Text: If you read an opinion that sounds clever because of masterful use of the English language, but you're still feeling conflicted, stick to your gut instinct. Leave trying to make sense of the tweet. You don't need it. There are other sources to gain knowledge and information from.

Text: Bhavana could have chosen to withdraw and gone on an entirely different trajectory post the crime. That was a choice she could've made. She has stood her ground, been clear that no matter what happens, even with the endless legal nightmares, she will continue to seek justice.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: I'm glad that media houses respected her need for privacy until now. Survivors need to be told of their rights & be allowed to exercise them. I hope members of other film industries too can rally behind and care for their colleagues.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: I'm glad Bhavana could feel ready enough to share. I'm glad-der she took her time and made her wellbeing her priority, every single day. It's heartening to read that counterparts check in on her. I hope the media doesn't harangue her now that she has started speaking in public.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: As journalists, it's important to check in with sources if they're truly ready to speak about their traumatic experiences. Pushing them to share is insensitive. Yes, their story is important.. needs to be told. But they come first. And their well-being comes first.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Healing isn't a linear process. Survival is a daily, everlasting process, hence they're called survivors. You live with it and the irreparable effects that come with it. Help each other to heal, as a community. Healing first.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Reading about trauma & the human brain, and the varied kinds of trauma, from sexual violence to war exposure to domestic abuse to witnessing the death of a loved one to childhood neglect, helps one understand better. That should then lead to empathy.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: As a survivor of traumatic life events, I have spent an entire lifetime trying to tell people, particularly men who don't grasp how gender based violence works, how trauma works, and the ways in which one can support and prioritise the healing of our traumatised loved ones.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: When it's something that happened in one's own industry & the accused is a public figure, there's no way one can avoid reminders, so, imagine how hard it must be for her. She moved to another industry and city, leaving behind her own, where she debuted at 16. That's trauma.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: When healing hasn't happened, exposing the self to further reminders of the trauma is just too much. There's a reason why survivors don't want to keep visiting police stations and courts to speak about what happened to them over and over again.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Trauma's effects on the mind & body, let alone to career, can be lasting. The neurobiology of trauma must be understood, to help survivors understand their experiences in a way that promotes their healing and reduces victim blaming in cases of gender-based violence.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Why is the survivor of trauma the one responsible for 'proving' it happened? How long has she had to go to courts and speak of it, and then watch lawyers handling the case quit? Hear trolls and channels speak ill of her? This is how one repeatedly retraumatises a person.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: When there's a wound, what do you do? You try to stop the bleeding. You won't wear tight-fitting clothes which can cause stress to the area. You will also close the wound soon, so, that it can heal faster. Exposed wounds lead to pain, fever and other inflammatory responses, etc
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: Bhavana not wanting to work in Malayalam films is a result of retraumatising the traumatised. Going back to the city where she was working, with its studios, industry members, all those who are privy to the case... It's easy to tell people to face fears. Trauma isn't mere fear.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text:
RT @LeeFlower : So yes, mechanical, in that there's no chemical reaction--new molecules are not being formed. The soap is not changing.

But viral and bacterial particles sure get changed by the encounter, and by changed I mean ded.

Mechanical at the molecular level. Stabby stab stab.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: RT @LeeFlower : But it's not just that soap makes things slippery and rinses them off. One end of a soap molecule makes things slippery; the other end stabs germs until they break open and then sticks to their denatured guts.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text: RT @LeeFlower : This is ALSO why soap is good at washing off dirt and grime; that same water-repulsed (hydrophobic) end is attracted to oil, dirt, etc, and sticks to them. A bunch of soap molecules do that at once and the substance is encased in soap, and rinses away.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text:
RT @LeeFlower : Basically, one end of a soap molecule is repelled by water and wants to not be in water.

So when it sees the lipid layer of a virus or bacteria (its 'skin' if you will), it goes "ooh, shelter from this icky water! let me just--push myself on in...oh, the shelter is leaking out."
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈

Text:
RT @LeeFlower : I had a conversation the other day with someone who thought "soap is mechanical" meant  it doesn't actually kill germs and just wipes them away.

Soap kills germs. It just does so mechanically, with crowbar-shaped molecules that pry open germs and spill their viscera.
Name: Manasa R • മാനസ 🌈
